    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I'd be happy to help with that. L1 and L2 regularization are both techniques used to prevent overfitting in machine learning models, but they handle the model coefficients differently. L1 regularization, also known as Lasso, tends to drive some coefficients to zero, effectively performing feature selection. This means that it can help you identify the most important features in your dataset. On the other hand, L2 regularization, also known as Ridge, penalizes the sum of the squared coefficients, which tends to shrink them but not necessarily to zero. This can help to reduce the impact of less important features without completely removing them. In essence, L1 regularization can help you find a simpler model with fewer features, while L2 regularization helps you find a more stable model with smaller but non-zero coefficients.",
